H0.text: Blinking is a behavior that humans learn, not an innate skill, because humans are born knowing some things and learn others, as Monica understood.

H1.text: Breathing is a behavior that humans learn, as Monica learned that humans are born knowing some things and learn others.

H2.text: Crying is a behavior humans learn.

H3.text: Swimming is a behavior that humans learn, rather than an ability that they are born with.

A4.text: Human babies demonstrate an innate swimming or diving reflex from newborn until approximately ten months.

A5.text: Newborns can instinctively hold their breath underwater and exhibit rudimentary swimming movements as part of a survival reflex.

A6.text: The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) recommends swimming lessons for children from 1â€“4, along with other precautionary measures to prevent drowning.

A7.text: Children were traditionally viewed not to be able to swim independently until 4 years of age, but infant swimming lessons are now recommended to prevent drowning and increase water familiarity.

A8.text: The swimming schools teach front and back floating and gliding with face in the water, open eyes under water.

A9.text: The swimming test includes swimming continuously of 500 yards, including back and front crawl at 100 yards, plus 50 yards for each of butterfly, backstroke, breaststroke and sidestroke.
